NEWCASTLE DISEASE, POULTRY - GREECE (02): OIE
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Thu, 7 Apr 2005
From: OIE Animal Health Information Department <information.dept@oie.int>
Source: OIE Alert message 050407GRC, 7 Apr 2005 [edited]

Newcastle disease [NCD] in Greece
---------------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of Newcastle disease in Greece reported to the
OIE: Dec 2004).
Information received on 6 Apr 2005 from Dr Vasilios Stylas, Head, Animal
Health Directorate, Ministry of Agriculture, Athens:
Report date: 6 Apr 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease in a
country, zone/compartment following a report declaring the outbreak(s)
ended. [See explanatory note for the inclusion of this reason within the
notification. - Mod.AS]
Date of first confirmation of the event: 5 Apr 2005.
Date of start of the event: 8 Mar 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, post-mortem and laboratory.
Virus intracerebral pathogenicity index: 1.625.
Details of outbreak:
First administrative division: Central Macedonia.
Lower administrative division: Kilkis.
Name of the location: village of Leventochori (10 km apart from the town of
Kilkis).
Number of susceptible animals (chickens of different ages) in the outbreak:
35 000.
Number of deaths: 3880.
Number of animals destroyed: 31 120.
Source of outbreak: unknown or inconclusive.
Control measure undertaken:
- stamping out;
- zoning;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s).
Other details/comments:
- The infected farm consists of 5 houses located on private land. At the
time of the suspicion, 4 of them were full of chicken and one house was empty.
- A few other farms exist in a distance of more than 10 km away. All of
these farms are vaccinated against Newcastle disease. The strict
surveillance that has been carried out for one month now in these farms has
not shown any clinical sign of Newcastle disease.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Recently, lists A and B in OIE's Terrestrial International Animal Health
Code have been united to a single, common list. The current NCD chapter is
2.7.13, within Section 2.7, "Avian diseases":
<http://oie.int/eng/normes/mcode/en_chapitre_2.7.13.htm>
According to the revised Code's requirements, immediate notification from a
member-country (by telegram, fax or e-mail), within 24 hours, is required
in any of the 6 following events:
1. 1st occurrence of a listed disease and/or infection in a country or
zone/compartment;
2. re-occurrence of a listed disease and/or infection in a country or
zone/compartment following a report declared the outbreak ended;
3. 1st occurrence of a new strain of a pathogen of an OIE listed disease in
a country or zone/compartment;
4. a sudden and unexpected increase in the distribution, incidence,
morbidity or mortality of a listed disease prevalent within a country or
zone/compartment;
5. an emerging disease with significant morbidity or mortality, or zoonotic
potential;
6. evidence of change in the epidemiology of a listed disease (including
host range, pathogenicity, strain) in particular if there is a zoonotic impact.
The Greek notification complies with the requirements related to event 2. -
Mod.AS]
